<h1>One-Page Resume Rules: When and How to Stick to One Page</h1>
<div class="meta">May 2026 &middot; 6 min read &middot; ðŸž Resume Tips</div>
<h2>The Evolution of the One-Page Rule</h2>
<p>The "one-page resume" rule originated in an era when recruiters received physical paper resumes. Today, digital resumes and ATS systems have changed the game. While one page is still ideal for many professionals, the rigid one-page rule has relaxed significantly. The real rule is: one page if you can, two if you need to, but never three.</p>
<h2>When One Page Is Essential</h2>
<p>Early-career professionals with less than 5 years of experience should stick to one page. Entry-level candidates, recent graduates, and career changers with limited relevant experience also benefit from the discipline of a one-page format. If your one-page resume has significant white space, you don't yet have enough experience for a second page.</p>
<h2>How to Fit Everything on One Page</h2>
<p><strong>Cut ruthlessly:</strong> Remove every bullet point that doesn't directly support your target role. Delete early-career jobs that are more than 10-15 years old or completely unrelated. Reduce your education section to the essentials after your first job. Tighten your margins slightly (0.5-0.7 inches is acceptable). Use a font size of 10-11 points. Remove any content that's obvious or generic.</p>
<h2>When Two Pages Are Acceptable</h2>
<p>Two pages are appropriate for mid-to-senior professionals with 10+ years of experience, technical roles requiring detailed project descriptions, academic and research positions, and executive or leadership roles. The key is that the second page must contain genuinely valuable information, not filler.</p>
